@Steve L

Seems like you and me solved the same puzz!

Ditto and amen to your writeup!

@Fact Boy

Of course you are correct about AWOL and desertion being distinct crimes in the UCMJ, but as used in the clue, I read “deserters” as a generic term for something like “people who wrongfully abandon their duties”, rather than a reference to “people who have committed the crime of ‘desertion’, as defined in the UCMJ”.

Personally, I assumed the clue writer was aware of the distinction between AWOL and desertion, and did that on purpose…

@Fact Boy

Often: misdirection. In this case, I just thought it was meant to be a low-key Easter egg, as the answer was too obvious for the clue to create any real confusion.

But I could be wrong — the editors might have actually conflated AWOL and desertion when they wrote/reviewed the entry.

@Anonymous
If you’ve served in the Armed Forces, you’d understand that the OP wasn’t criticizing the creator or editors. I read his perspective and immediately recognized that it evoked certain memories for him.

I viewed his post as a nostalgic trip down memory lane, rather than a criticism.

@Jerry

a) Yes, I have served in the US military. And?

b) I got (and continue to get) the impression that OP intended to point out an error  in the clue. That’s fine by me. Their post was respectful and well-written, and I appreciated it — I just see things a little differently.

